1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:07,632
You're listening to: FOMOA for Developers: OpenAI-Compatible API, Deep Research & Ethical Crawling.

2
00:00:07,632 --> 00:00:24,038
The complete FOMOA developer guide — a drop-in OpenAI-compatible endpoint, multi-hop deep research, an ethical web-crawl API that respects robots.txt, and entity search over 50,000+ Indian companies and schemes.

3
00:00:24,038 --> 00:00:25,096
Let's get started.

4
00:00:25,096 --> 00:00:30,504
If you have ever wired an app to the OpenAI API, you already know how to use FOMOA.

5
00:00:30,504 --> 00:00:40,096
That is the whole point: FOMOA exposes an OpenAI-compatible endpoint, so you change one line — the base_url — and keep the rest of your code.

6
00:00:40,096 --> 00:00:49,206
On top of that drop-in chat API, it adds India-optimised search plus four purpose-built endpoints for research, crawling, and entity lookup.

7
00:00:49,206 --> 00:00:58,677
This guide consolidates the developer story: the compatible chat API, deep research, ethical crawling, and entity/company search.

8
00:00:58,677 --> 00:01:03,858
For the product overview and how the model was trained, start with the complete FOMOA guide.

9
00:01:03,858 --> 00:01:07,163
Now, let's talk about Drop-In OpenAI Replacement.

10
00:01:07,163 --> 00:01:11,430
The migration is deliberately boring — which is exactly what you want:

11
00:01:11,430 --> 00:01:21,622
Because it speaks the OpenAI wire format, it works with anything built on that format — the official SDK, LangChain, LlamaIndex, and your existing streaming code.

12
00:01:21,622 --> 00:01:22,512
Streaming.

13
00:01:22,512 --> 00:01:30,564
If you are designing the API layer around this, the usual rules apply — sensible status codes, idempotency, and backpressure.

14
00:01:30,564 --> 00:01:37,055
I wrote those up in REST API design best practices and rate limiting & API gateway patterns.

15
00:01:37,055 --> 00:01:39,795
Moving on to The India-Specific Endpoints.

16
00:01:39,795 --> 00:01:48,413
Beyond /v1/chat/completions, FOMOA exposes four endpoints that a generic chat model does not give you:

17
00:01:48,413 --> 00:01:49,963
Endpoint, Purpose.

18
00:01:49,963 --> 00:01:55,673
/api/answer, A direct, cited answer to a single question.

19
00:01:55,673 --> 00:02:01,574
/api/research, Multi-hop deep research with conflict detection.

20
00:02:01,574 --> 00:02:06,093
/api/crawl, Ethical web-content extraction.

21
00:02:06,093 --> 00:02:12,355
/api/entities, Structured search over Indian companies & schemes.

22
00:02:12,355 --> 00:02:16,454
/api/answer — direct cited answers.

23
00:02:16,454 --> 00:02:26,165
When you want a single grounded answer rather than a chat turn, /api/answer returns the response with its citations, so you can show users where each claim came from.

24
00:02:26,165 --> 00:02:30,180
Next up: Deep Research: Multi-Hop, Conflict-Aware.

25
00:02:30,180 --> 00:02:33,689
A normal search does one query and returns links.

26
00:02:33,689 --> 00:02:45,889
Multi-hop research uses the results of the first search to decide what to search next — following leads the way a human researcher would — then synthesises a cited report and flags where sources disagree.

27
00:02:45,889 --> 00:02:50,432
FOMOA offers three depths so you can trade latency for thoroughness:

28
00:02:50,432 --> 00:02:53,557
Quick (~5s) — a fast single-pass answer..

29
00:02:53,557 --> 00:02:57,908
Normal (~15s) — a couple of hops, good for most questions..

30
00:02:57,908 --> 00:03:03,810
Deep (~60s) — up to three hops, conflict detection, and a structured report..

31
00:03:03,810 --> 00:03:18,185
The conflicts[] array is the interesting part: instead of silently picking one number when two sources disagree, it returns both and tells you which source is more authoritative — the same credibility ranking described in the complete FOMOA guide.

32
00:03:18,185 --> 00:03:23,750
This is what makes it usable for journalists, analysts, and anyone who has to defend an answer.

33
00:03:23,750 --> 00:03:26,021
Let's explore Ethical Web Crawling.

34
00:03:26,021 --> 00:03:34,567
/api/crawl extracts clean, readable content from a URL — but with guardrails that a naive scraper skips:

35
00:03:34,567 --> 00:03:36,971
Respects robots.txt.

36
00:03:36,971 --> 00:03:40,637
If a site disallows crawling, FOMOA does not crawl it..

37
00:03:40,637 --> 00:03:46,021
Rate-limited to ~2 requests/second per site so you do not hammer anyone's server..

38
00:03:46,021 --> 00:03:51,430
Returns clean text, links, and metadata rather than raw HTML soup..

39
00:03:51,430 --> 00:04:00,396
It supports single-page, site-wide, and sitemap-based modes, handles pagination, and degrades gracefully on JavaScript-heavy pages.

40
00:04:00,396 --> 00:04:09,843
The ethical defaults matter: building data pipelines on top of a crawler that ignores robots.txt is how you get your IPs blocked and your project shut down.

41
00:04:09,843 --> 00:04:13,725
Now let's look at Entity Search: Indian Companies & Schemes.

42
00:04:13,725 --> 00:04:26,406
/api/entities is structured search over India-specific entities — most usefully, 50,000+ Indian startups and companies and the catalogue of government schemes.

43
00:04:26,426 --> 00:04:33,034
You can filter by industry, location, and funding stage (and combine them), or pass a natural-language query.

44
00:04:33,034 --> 00:04:43,383
For the scheme side — eligibility, documents, official links — see the use-case walkthroughs in FOMOA vs Exa.ai + India Use-Cases.

45
00:04:43,383 --> 00:04:45,847
Now, let's talk about Framework Integrations.

46
00:04:45,847 --> 00:04:51,363
Because the chat endpoint is OpenAI-compatible, framework integration is trivial:

47
00:04:51,363 --> 00:04:58,635
LlamaIndex works the same way — point its OpenAI-compatible LLM wrapper at FOMOA's base_url.

48
00:04:58,635 --> 00:05:01,303
Moving on to Error Handling and Rate Limits.

49
00:05:01,303 --> 00:05:03,851
Treat it like any production dependency:

50
00:05:03,851 --> 00:05:06,592
Handle 429s with backoff.

51
00:05:06,592 --> 00:05:12,806
Respect the documented per-key limits and retry with exponential backoff and jitter..

52
00:05:12,806 --> 00:05:18,695
Set timeouts, especially for deep research (which can legitimately take ~60s)..

53
00:05:18,695 --> 00:05:25,895
Cache repeated answers where freshness allows — the same caching discipline I cover in Redis caching strategies..

54
00:05:25,895 --> 00:05:28,070
Next up: Why This Matters.

55
00:05:28,070 --> 00:05:39,741
The combination is what is rare: an OpenAI-compatible chat API you can adopt in five minutes, plus research, crawl, and entity endpoints tuned for Indian data — at zero cost.

